    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4409292412" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4409292412" />
    <a title="Czarny Pies" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29160274-czarny-pies"><img alt="Czarny Pies" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1400687408p2/29160274.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4409292412?book_show_action=true">Dec 27, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Czarny Pies" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Czarny Pies" href="/user/show/29160274-czarny-pies">Czarny Pies</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Those who have read Anne Applebaum's &quot;Red Famine&quot;</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Czarny by: </span>
      Joseph Brodsky
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29160274-czarny-pies?shelf=russian-lit">russian-lit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4409292412" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14574226644360266711">One inevitably has a feeling of déjà-vu reading &quot;The Foundation Pit&quot; which is anti-soviet dystopian novel written during the early 1930s but not published until 1969 and not available in English translation until 1973. The work is very close in mood and subject matter to George Orwell&apos;s &quot;1984&quot;.One difference is that Orwell&apos;s novel focuses on the &quot;Great Purge&quot; of 1936-1938 during which 700,000 to 1,200,000 Soviet citizens died in Gulags whereas Platonov focuses on the Great Famine of 1933 in whic</span>
  <span id="freeText14574226644360266711" style="display:none">One inevitably has a feeling of déjà-vu reading "The Foundation Pit" which is anti-soviet dystopian novel written during the early 1930s but not published until 1969 and not available in English translation until 1973. The work is very close in mood and subject matter to George Orwell's "1984".One difference is that Orwell's novel focuses on the "Great Purge" of 1936-1938 during which 700,000 to 1,200,000 Soviet citizens died in Gulags whereas Platonov focuses on the Great Famine of 1933 in which 3,000,000 to 4,000,000 Soviet peasants starved to death during the force collectivization of agriculture.<br />The most important difference between the two works for the typical GR reader however is probably that Orwell wrote for the English and American public whereas Platonov wrote for his fellow Russians. Orwell's book is simply easier to understand for those of us who live in the West than is Platonov's which is not difficult per se but rather contains points that will be missed by someone unfamiliar with the historical context. My advice for those unfamiliar with the events would be to read Anne Applebaum's "Red Famine" first.<br />Joseph Brodsky, the winner of the 1987 Nobel Prize for Literature, expressed the opinion in his brilliant essay on Platonov, that "The Foundation Pit" was as great as anything written by Joyce, Musil or Kafka and then added that "such ratings are in poor taste". As someone with an MBA, I would contest that they are in bad taste. Rather they are good marketing. Brodsky wanted me to read the book and convinced me to do so. I think "The Foundation Pit" is as good as Brodsky says it is but feel that the way to get the most out of it would be to read first either Applebaum's "Red Famine" or Robert Conquest's "Harvest of Sorrow" which is as good but much harder to get a hold of.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14574226644360266711" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review4409292412">
  <td colspan="2">
    <div class="updateActionLinks">
        <a class="right flag" rel="nofollow" id="flag_link4409292412" title="Flag this review as inappropriate." href="/flagged/new?resource_id=4409292412&amp;resource_type=Review&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F715995.The_Foundation_Pit">flag</a>





      <span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_review_4409292412'><a id="like_count_review_4409292412" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/4409292412?resource_type=Review"><span class="likesCount">4 likes</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it gr-button gr-button--small" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F715995.The_Foundation_Pit">Like</a></span>
&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a href="/review/show/4409292412?book_show_action=true&amp;from_review_page=1">see review</a>
    </div>


    <div id='comments_for_review_4409292412' style='display: none;'>
</div>

  </td>
</tr>

      </div>

  </div>

