  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4445505500" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4445505500" />
    <a title="Hadrian" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4100763-hadrian"><img alt="Hadrian" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1640488227p2/4100763.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4445505500?book_show_action=true">Jan 04, 2022</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hadrian" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hadrian" href="/user/show/4100763-hadrian">Hadrian</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4100763-hadrian?shelf=russia">russia</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4100763-hadrian?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4445505500" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4732855318758311003"><i>On the day of the thirtieth anniversary of his private life, Voshchev was made redundant from the small machine factory where he obtained the means for his own existence. His dismissal notice stated that he was being removed from production on account of weakening strength in him and thoughtfulness amid the general tempo of labor.</i><br/><br/>An almost unutterably bleak story. I&apos;ve heard so much praise about it, and it only became more difficult to read. Voshchev is fired for standing still and thinking abou</span>
  <span id="freeText4732855318758311003" style="display:none"><i>On the day of the thirtieth anniversary of his private life, Voshchev was made redundant from the small machine factory where he obtained the means for his own existence. His dismissal notice stated that he was being removed from production on account of weakening strength in him and thoughtfulness amid the general tempo of labor.</i><br /><br />An almost unutterably bleak story. I've heard so much praise about it, and it only became more difficult to read. Voshchev is fired for standing still and thinking about future plans for a better life, and he is sent to another work place - a giant foundation pit for a future House of the Proletariat. The pit grows deeper and wider, and then stories of progressively worse violence, terror, waste. Then, as the common misquotation of Chairman Mao goes: "It's always darkest before it's totally black." A bear denounces and eats the rich peasants. A priest denounces his own congregation, and he gets a punch in the mouth for his trouble. People who surrender their property too quickly or too enthusiastically are treated with suspicion. <br /><br />Platonov lived in the Soviet Union for much of his life, and the ending essay suggests he was a true believer -- but one who was deeply cynical towards Stalinist collectivization and the increasing absurdity of Five-Year Plans. The edition of the book I read was studded with endnotes, explaining so many slogans; but also so many folk beliefs about animals, or bones, etc. <br /><br />The story may have had a literal inspiration. In 1931, the Cathedral of Christ the Savior was demolished in Moscow to prepare for the construction of a planned Palace of the Soviets. Building designs were shown off, a great foundation was dug, some scattered girders arose, and the building was never finished - the war prevented any further construction on that scale. When Stalin died and Khrushchev took over, the worlds largest swimming pool was built on the site in 1958. Then in the 1990s, the pool was filled in and the cathedral was rebuilt. Life imitates art. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4732855318758311003" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


