      </div>

  </div>

  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>

    </div>
  </div>
    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3064831000" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3064831000" />
    <a title="Walker White" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/97292639-walker-white"><img alt="Walker White" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1559664097p2/97292639.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3064831000?book_show_action=true">Dec 10, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Walker White" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Walker White" href="/user/show/97292639-walker-white">Walker White</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781590173053" href="/book/show/4270942-the-foundation-pit">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/97292639-walker-white?shelf=own">own</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/97292639-walker-white?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3064831000" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10814243155228236139">Platonov’s profoundly unique novel, The Foundation Pit, is subversive to its very core. Every possible trope of state sanctioned literature and state ideology is upended, inverted, questioned, and ultimately proven to be empty, desolate, and destructive. Platonov achieves this effect through his use of language, often so idiotic that it is brilliant. He disfigures language the way total collectivization disfigured the countryside, forcefully removing it of its soul. Along these lines, Platonov d</span>
  <span id="freeText10814243155228236139" style="display:none">Platonov’s profoundly unique novel, The Foundation Pit, is subversive to its very core. Every possible trope of state sanctioned literature and state ideology is upended, inverted, questioned, and ultimately proven to be empty, desolate, and destructive. Platonov achieves this effect through his use of language, often so idiotic that it is brilliant. He disfigures language the way total collectivization disfigured the countryside, forcefully removing it of its soul. Along these lines, Platonov dehumanizes emotion by describing it with the language of communist propaganda and state slogans. This technique also allows Platonov to reveal the absolute normalization of violence that collectivization wrought, particularly in Zachev’s veiled and threatening speech. In this distortion of language Platonov reveals the false promise (promulgated by false prophets) of the Communist Utopia, which is in itself a concept that Platonov originally believed in and strove for.<br /> <br />	The image of the Communist Utopia that one imagines—stretching gloriously to the secular heavens as a sort of futuristic tower of Babel, a magnificent patriarchal structure with Lenin standing monumentally at its peak…—this imagined utopia is ingeniously inverted by Platonov, with Nastya and her mother buried at the bottom of the massive foundation pit for the never to be realized utopia, which is essentially a mass grave. Both peasants and workers, both the hammer and sickle, are buried here. This structure is subversive in multiple ways, not the least of which is that it represents a matriarchy, with Nastya emblemizing the “failed socialist generation,” and her mother, perhaps even the motherland. However, any memory that the characters may have once had of the motherland before the revolution, of their own childhoods, and of human feeling itself is slowly blotted out, or, if you will, buried underneath the soil. For instance, it is alluded to that both Chiklin, the inimitable proletarian worker, and Prushevsky, the “engineer” of the Communist Utopia have had romantic encounters with Nastya’s mother. Yet, the bittersweet memory of this woman is buried and locked away behind a pile of rocks by Chiklin in the opening pages of the novel, only to be moved and buried with her daughter at the end. This, in a way, is both the past and the future that are being buried simultaneously. Indeed, in Platonov’s final pained and anxiety ridden authorial disclaimer, in which he cannot use the word “I,” he alludes to “the destruction not only of all the past but also of the future.” The Foundation Pit is a mythical, religious, atheist, communist, anticommunist parable and fairytale (and cautionarytale) that makes us understand that aforementioned destruction on both a linguistic and historical level. It is also a brilliant work of fiction that was produced under circumstances so strange and disturbing that to read the actual facts is perhaps more difficult still than it is to read this already difficult book. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10814243155228236139" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

